    <h1 class="text-center">Threat actor abuses Gophish to deliver new PowerRAT and DCRAT</h1>

    <div class="text-center m-1">
        <div class="post-author">
            <span>By </span>
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/chetan/">Chetan Raghuprasad</a>
        </div>

        <br/>
        <time class="post-datetime" datetime="October 22, 2024 06:00">
            Tuesday, October 22, 2024 06:00
        </time>

        <div class="m-3">
                            <a href="/category/rat/" class="category primary-category">
                                RAT
                            </a>
                                                    <a href="/category/threats/" class="category primary-category">
                                Threats
                            </a>
                                </div>
    </div>

    <section class="post-content-wrapper mt-5">
        <div class="post-content">
            <ul><li>Cisco Talos recently discovered a phishing campaign using an open-source phishing toolkit called <a href="https://github.com/gophish/gophish" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Gophish</u></a> by an unknown threat actor.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>The campaign involves modular infection chains that are either Maldoc or HTML-based infections and require the victim’s intervention to trigger the infection chain.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>Talos discovered an undocumented PowerShell RAT we’re calling PowerRAT,&nbsp; as one of the payloads and another infamous Remote Access Tool (RAT) DCRAT.&nbsp;</li><li>We found a few placeholders for base64 encoded PowerShell scripts in the PowerRAT, indicating that the threat actor is actively developing their tools.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul><h1 id="victimology">Victimology&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos assesses with high confidence that the threat actor is targeting Russian-speaking users based on the language used in the Phishing emails, luring contents of Malicious documents, a masqueraded HTML webpage of Vkontake (VK), a popular social media application amongst Russian speakers, especially in Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Azerbaijan.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p></p><h1 id="actor-uses-gophish-to-send-phishing-emails">Actor uses Gophish to send phishing emails&nbsp;</h1><p>Our analysis of the malicious hyperlinks embedded in the phishing emails disclosed to us the attacker-controlled hosting domains disk-yanbex[.]ru delivered the Malicious Microsoft Word document, and an HTML file embedded with the malicious JavaScript.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The domain disk-yanbex[.]ru resolves to the IP address 34[.]236[.]234[.]165, an AWS EC2 instance with the fully qualified domain name ec2-34-236-234-165[.]compute-1[.]amazonaws[.]com, during our analysis. We also observed that the same server 34[.]236[.]234[.]165 was reverse resolving to another domain e-connection[.]ru, which also delivered malicious JavaScript-embedded HTML files. Our further analysis of the server 34[.]236[.]234[.]165 disclosed to us that the actor hosted the Gophish toolkit on the server running at port number 3333. <a href="https://github.com/gophish/gophish" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Gophish</u></a> is an Open-Source easy-to-deploy phishing toolkit that is developed to conduct security awareness training according to the tool’s developer. &nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-a47cae3e-74fc-48ed-b7fc-891fcbc16d1d-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="500" height="500"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Attacker hosting Gophish.</span></figcaption></figure><p>Talos analysis of the phishing email sample’s header showed us that the email was first delivered from server 34[.]236[.]234[.]165, indicating that the threat actor is misusing the Gophish framework in this campaign to deliver phishing emails to their targets.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-0b19a190-616a-4964-a3dd-7ba075e54c14.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="1168" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-0b19a190-616a-4964-a3dd-7ba075e54c14.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-0b19a190-616a-4964-a3dd-7ba075e54c14.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-0b19a190-616a-4964-a3dd-7ba075e54c14.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sample Phishing email header.&nbsp;</span></figcaption></figure><h1 id="multi-modular-campaign-delivers-powerrat-and-dcrat">Multi-modular Campaign delivers PowerRAT and DCRAT&nbsp;&nbsp;</h1><p>The campaign has two initial attack vectors, one based on malicious Word documents and another based on HTML files containing malicious JavaScript. Upon activation, these would lead to the download and activation of PowerRAT or DCRAT depending on the initial vector. Both the attack chains require user intervention to trigger the infections on the compromised machines.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-8a7bb4a5-b58b-4e29-bfbc-86206837c666.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="1098" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-8a7bb4a5-b58b-4e29-bfbc-86206837c666.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-8a7bb4a5-b58b-4e29-bfbc-86206837c666.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-8a7bb4a5-b58b-4e29-bfbc-86206837c666.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h1 id="maldoc-based-infection-delivers-powerrat">Maldoc-based infection delivers PowerRAT&nbsp;</h1><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-31dd1180-86de-49b7-8869-e1b7667bd22c.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="809" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-31dd1180-86de-49b7-8869-e1b7667bd22c.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-31dd1180-86de-49b7-8869-e1b7667bd22c.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-31dd1180-86de-49b7-8869-e1b7667bd22c.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>When a victim opens the Microsoft Word document and enables the view contents button displayed in the document banner, the malicious VB macro program executes.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-265ba20d-5358-4b3d-a872-a7b0a9e43f97.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="170" height="72"></figure><p>The macro program initially executes a function that decodes or translates specific encoded symbols in the lure contents of the Word document into their corresponding characters from another alphabet in Cyrillic, transforming the lure contents into readable form.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-93568815-92bb-41d9-9885-0e8a56dd1f03.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="765" height="479" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-93568815-92bb-41d9-9885-0e8a56dd1f03.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-93568815-92bb-41d9-9885-0e8a56dd1f03.png 765w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>We spotted a base64 encoded data blob on the third page of the Word document and the actor used the text color the same as that of the document's default background color, hiding them from the victim’s view.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-fb0ca5d1-d20d-4e5f-a268-7ece44b3fa6b.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="714" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-fb0ca5d1-d20d-4e5f-a268-7ece44b3fa6b.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-fb0ca5d1-d20d-4e5f-a268-7ece44b3fa6b.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-fb0ca5d1-d20d-4e5f-a268-7ece44b3fa6b.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>To identify the hidden encoded data, the macro executes a function that searches for specific strings such as “DigitalRSASignature:” and “CHECKSUM” in the content section of the Word document, and when found, it copies the data following the search strings to an array.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-8fdeb4df-fb37-4319-a6d2-532efe910b26.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="553" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-8fdeb4df-fb37-4319-a6d2-532efe910b26.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-8fdeb4df-fb37-4319-a6d2-532efe910b26.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-8fdeb4df-fb37-4319-a6d2-532efe910b26.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>To decode the base64 encoded data blob, the actor uses a custom function called CheckContent() in the macro. It removes any “=” characters which are the padding characters in the encoded data blob and decodes them into two parts in a byte array. The first part is the contents of a malicious HTML application (HTA) file and the second is a PowerShell loader.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-402eacb6-c297-4bd9-ac10-085533f02586.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1236" height="726" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-402eacb6-c297-4bd9-ac10-085533f02586.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-402eacb6-c297-4bd9-ac10-085533f02586.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-402eacb6-c297-4bd9-ac10-085533f02586.png 1236w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The macro drops the decoded contents of the malicious HTA file to “UserCache.ini.hta” and the PowerShell loader into “UserCache.ini” in the victim machine's current user profile folder.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-bcc5855e-017c-46fa-a428-bd935342557d.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1251" height="763" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-bcc5855e-017c-46fa-a428-bd935342557d.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-bcc5855e-017c-46fa-a428-bd935342557d.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-bcc5855e-017c-46fa-a428-bd935342557d.png 1251w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The actor has abused the Windows NT current version autorun registry key called “LOAD”. The registry key “HKEY_CURRENT_USER\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\LOAD” is used by Windows to automatically launch applications or processes when a user logs into their account. Specifically, this key stores information about programs that are set to load upon user login. It works similarly to other startup mechanisms in Windows (such as the Startup folder or the Run registry keys), but this specific key is less commonly used. The macro after dropping the malicious HTA and the PowerShell loader script in the victim machine user profile folder, it configures the registry key “HKEY_CURRENT_USER\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\LOAD” with the value “C:\Users\&lt;Username&gt;\UserCache.ini.hta”.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-9539fbdd-6750-40ac-88c2-990f0187fe88.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1126" height="169" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-9539fbdd-6750-40ac-88c2-990f0187fe88.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-9539fbdd-6750-40ac-88c2-990f0187fe88.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-9539fbdd-6750-40ac-88c2-990f0187fe88.png 1126w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>Finally, the macro checks if there are any headers in the Word documents and deletes the contents of the headers from all sections of the Word document.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-c4ac63fe-6e57-4df2-bb19-c7199eebe1c4.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="376" height="168"></figure><h2 id="intermediate-phase-includes-malicious-hta-javascript-and-powershell-loader">Intermediate phase includes Malicious HTA, JavaScript, and PowerShell Loader&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2><p>The malicious HTA “UserCache.ini.hta” is executed through the LOAD registry key when a victim logs into the machine. It drops a JavaScript called “UserCacheHelper.lnk.js” in the victim machine user profile folder and writes a single line code embedding with a PowerShell command to execute the dropped PowerShell Loader masquerading as “UserCache.ini” file. The HTA file executes the JavaScript “UserCacheHelper.lnk.js” using the LOLbin “cscript.exe”.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-c124f75f-0652-4122-a076-2b8051294bfe.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="871" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-c124f75f-0652-4122-a076-2b8051294bfe.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-c124f75f-0652-4122-a076-2b8051294bfe.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-c124f75f-0652-4122-a076-2b8051294bfe.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sample of malicious HTA file.</span></figcaption></figure><p>The dropped JavaScript “UserCacheHelper.lnk.js” loads the contents of the “UserCache.ini” and executes it using the Invoke-Expression PowerShell command. The PowerShell Loader script masquerading as the INI file contains base64 encoded data blob&nbsp;of the payload PowerRAT, which decodes and executes in the victim’s machine memory.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-d04a122f-d62a-452b-a571-0b13c1500018.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="694" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-d04a122f-d62a-452b-a571-0b13c1500018.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-d04a122f-d62a-452b-a571-0b13c1500018.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-d04a122f-d62a-452b-a571-0b13c1500018.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sample PowerShell Loader script embedded with PowerRAT.</span></figcaption></figure><h1 id="powerrat-expands-the-attack-vector-for-further-infections">PowerRAT expands the attack vector for further infections&nbsp;&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos discovered a new PowerShell remote access tool as one of the payloads in this campaign we are calling PowerRAT that executes in the victim’s machine memory. It has the functionality of executing other PowerShell scripts or commands as directed by the C2 server, enabling the attack vector for further infections on the victim machine.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The PowerRAT that executes in the victim machine memory initially checks if the JavaScript “UserCacheHelper.lnk.js” exists in the user profile folder and if not found, it will reinfect the victim machine by performing the actions of the PowerShell loader script described in the previous section. Then it hides the “UserCache.ini” by modifying the file attributes to “Hidden”.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-4945d2d4-5f5e-45c9-ae23-f07d58ffbab2.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="960" height="840" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-4945d2d4-5f5e-45c9-ae23-f07d58ffbab2.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-4945d2d4-5f5e-45c9-ae23-f07d58ffbab2.png 960w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The PowerRAT performs reconnaissance on the victim’s machine by executing a function GetID() which collects the username, computer name, and the system driver letter through the PowerShell command Get-CimInstance. It also collects the drive serial number through the win32_volume class of WMIobject.&nbsp; The collected data is written to memory in the format &lt;Computername_Username_drive serial number&gt;.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-6d3bc6e9-b935-47d3-abb5-b88b4412de3f.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="897" height="268" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-6d3bc6e9-b935-47d3-abb5-b88b4412de3f.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-6d3bc6e9-b935-47d3-abb5-b88b4412de3f.png 897w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>After performing the reconnaissance, the PowerRAT attempts to connect to the C2 server by sending the collected data of the victim’s machine using a hardcoded URL through the HTTP GET method.&nbsp; The C2 servers identified in this campaign are 94[.]103[.]85[.]47 located in Russia with the ASN 48282 of Hosting Technology LTD and 5[.]252[.]176[.]55 also geographically located in Russia with the ASN 39798 of MivoCloud SRL.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-9ff609da-2789-4eed-8164-b509760eddb6.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="792" height="267" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-9ff609da-2789-4eed-8164-b509760eddb6.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-9ff609da-2789-4eed-8164-b509760eddb6.png 792w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>When there is no response from the C2 server, the PowerRAT has a placeholder function called offlineworker() that has the functionality to decode an embedded base64 encoded string of a PowerShell script and executes it using the Invoke-Expression command. The actor has built this functionality to keep the infection alive in the victim machine even if the victim's environment detects the malicious C2 traffic and blocks the connection. We didn’t see any embedded base64 encoded strings in the PowerRAT sample that we analyzed and is likely a placeholder, indicating that the actor is actively developing and updating their tools.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-66650147-e19c-4056-9eb6-ce1fc353acd5.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="287" height="163"></figure><p>The PowerRAT generates a random number between 7 - 23 and pauses its execution for (300 + random number) seconds and re-attempts to connect to the C2 server continuously waiting for a response. During our analysis, the C2 servers were not responding, and still, our further analysis of the PowerRAT showed us that the C2 server will likely respond with an XML configuration file having multiple modules with embedded base64 encoded PowerShell commands or scripts.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The PowerRAT has the functionality to parse the received XML file and search for the sections called config.&nbsp; It periodically executes the embedded encoded PowerShell commands or scripts, according to their defined intervals and run limits. The PowerRAT continues to run until all commands or scripts in the config sections are executed the required number of times.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-b6ea55cf-cd28-4da6-9ee3-cc6652c3014d.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="617" height="782" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-b6ea55cf-cd28-4da6-9ee3-cc6652c3014d.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-b6ea55cf-cd28-4da6-9ee3-cc6652c3014d.png 617w"></figure><h1 id="html-based-infection-delivers-dcrat">HTML-based infection delivers DCRAT&nbsp;</h1><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-66755b76-8e24-4351-b275-b85b357964cd.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="984" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-66755b76-8e24-4351-b275-b85b357964cd.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-66755b76-8e24-4351-b275-b85b357964cd.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-66755b76-8e24-4351-b275-b85b357964cd.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>Talos discovered that the threat actor is also using HTML files embedded with malicious JavaScript in this campaign that are delivered to the victims through the malicious links in the phishing email, leading to the infection of the DCRAT payload.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>When a victim clicks on the malicious link in the phishing email, a remotely located HTML file containing the malicious JavaScript opens in the victim machine’s browser and simultaneously executes the JavaScript. The JavaScript has a base64 encoded data blob of a 7-ZIP archive of a malicious SFXRAR executable. It decodes the embedded base64 encoded data blob into binary data blob with the type “application/octet-stream” in the memory. A download URL for the binary data blob is created using the URL.createObjectURL() method and assigned to a variable in memory. It calls the click() method on the URL of the binary data blob which triggers the download of the binary data to a 7-Zip archive file. The malicious 7-Zip archive masquerades as the VK messenger application archive file in one of the malicious HTML files and another with a Russian name. The actor is using this technique in the JavaScript function to masquerade as the actual download activity of a file over the internet through a browser. &nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-49240e46-727e-4ff8-a570-99753bc02e4e.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1431" height="463" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-49240e46-727e-4ff8-a570-99753bc02e4e.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-49240e46-727e-4ff8-a570-99753bc02e4e.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-49240e46-727e-4ff8-a570-99753bc02e4e.png 1431w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>A victim must inflate the 7-Zip archive manually to run the SFXRAR executable which is masquerading as the legitimate VK application executable which leads to DCRAT infection. The SFX RAR executable is packaged with the malicious loader or dropper executables, batch file, and a decoy document in some samples.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>When a victim runs the SFX executable, the SFX script drops the packaged files into a folder and executes the batch file which runs another password-protected SFXRAR with the hardcoded password “riverdD” and runs the DCRAT.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-57a34953-9361-4cae-8fde-f57baf05b481.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="336" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-57a34953-9361-4cae-8fde-f57baf05b481.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-57a34953-9361-4cae-8fde-f57baf05b481.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-57a34953-9361-4cae-8fde-f57baf05b481.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>In another sample, we observed that the SFXRAR drops the GOLoader and the decoy document Excel spreadsheet in the victim machine user profile applications temporary folder and runs the GOLoader along with opening the decoy document.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-a0029e53-3e79-49e4-b8e9-08c5978bc974.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="223" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-a0029e53-3e79-49e4-b8e9-08c5978bc974.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/10/data-src-image-a0029e53-3e79-49e4-b8e9-08c5978bc974.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-a0029e53-3e79-49e4-b8e9-08c5978bc974.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>Talos observed an overlap of the technique used by the threat actor in this campaign with an earlier <a href="https://hunt.io/blog/spotting-sparkrat-detection-tactics-and-sandbox-findings" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>SparkRAT</u></a> attack reported by Hunt researchers in April 2024, indicating that SparkRAT is another payload in the threat actor’s arsenal.&nbsp;</p><h2 id="goloader-downloads-and-runs-the-dcrat">GOLoader downloads and runs the DCRAT&nbsp;</h2><p>In DCRAT infection, the SFX script runs a malicious Loader executable and simultaneously opens a decoy document. The malicious loader executable we are calling “GOLoader” is compiled in Golang. It modifies the configuration settings for Microsoft Defender Antivirus, specifically by excluding the root directory “C:\” and the folder “C:\Users\$user\Desktop” in the victim machine by executing the PowerShell commands.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<html>
<body>

    <table>
        <tr>
            <td>powershell -Command Add-MpPreference -ExclusionPath 'C:\Users\$user\Desktop'</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>powershell -Command Add-MpPreference -ExclusionPath 'C:\'</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

</body>
</html>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<p>After configuring the exclusion paths, the GOLoader downloads the DCRAT binary data stream from a remote location through a hardcoded URL and writes it into a dropped executable with the file name “file.exe” in the desktop folder on the victim’s machine. During our analysis, we found that the remote location URL hardcoded in the GOLoader was pointing to a GitHub repository, which was not accessible. However, we found that the hosted payload binary in the GitHub repository is the Dark Crystal RAT (DCRAT) binary based on open-source intelligence data.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-53b5692e-4487-487b-b970-b1213fcd6edb.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="619" height="804" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/10/data-src-image-53b5692e-4487-487b-b970-b1213fcd6edb.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/10/data-src-image-53b5692e-4487-487b-b970-b1213fcd6edb.png 619w"></figure><h2 id="threat-actor-delivers-dcrat">Threat actor delivers DCRAT&nbsp;</h2><p>The payload Dark Crystal RAT (DCRAT) sample that we analyzed in this campaign is a modular RAT associated with plugins to perform the DLL injection and information stealing tasks.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Key features of the DCRAT sample of this campaign include:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Provides remote control access to the victim machine to the actor who can execute arbitrary commands, manage files, and monitor user activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>It has the capability of downloading and executing other files on the victim's machine.&nbsp;</li><li>With its stealer plugin modules, the RAT can steal sensitive information including credentials, files, and financial information from the victim's machine.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>The RAT can take screenshots and capture the keystrokes on the victim's machine.&nbsp;</li><li>We found that the RAT creates multiple copies of its binary masquerading as legitimate Windows executables including csrss.exe, dllhost.exe, taskhostw.exe, and winlogon.exe in the folders such as ProgramData, Pictures, Saved Games, and Windows start menu. It drops the embedded modules in the administrator user desktop folder using random file names and with the “.log” file extension.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul>

            <td>schtasks.exe /create /tn "filef" /sc MINUTE /mo 13 /tr "'C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\file.exe'" /f</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>schtasks.exe /create /tn "file" /sc ONLOGON /tr "'C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\file.exe'" /rl HIGHEST /f</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>schtasks.exe /create /tn "filef" /sc MINUTE /mo 9 /tr "'C:\Users\admin\AppData\Local\Temp\file.exe'" /rl HIGHEST /f</td>
        </tr>

<ul><li>The RAT communicates to the C2 server through a URL hardcoded in the RAT configuration file as shown in the picture and exfiltrates the sensitive data collected from the victim machine.
